SIMPLE: pinch
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pinch
<hw>Pinch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Pinched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pinching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>pincer</ets>, probably
fr. OD. <ets>pitsen</ets> to pinch; akin to G. <ets>pfetzen</ets> to
cut, pinch; perhaps of Celtic origin. Cf. <er>Piece</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To press hard or squeeze between the ends of the
fingers, between teeth or claws, or between the jaws of an instrument;
to squeeze or compress, as between any two hard bodies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to seize; to grip; to bite; -- said of
animals.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He [the hound] <qex>pinched</qex> and pulled her down.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To plait.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Full seemly her wimple <qex>ipinched</qex> was.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Figuratively: To cramp; to straiten; to oppress; to
starve; to distress; <as>as, to be <ex>pinched</ex> for
money</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Want of room . . . <qex>pinching</qex> a whole nation.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To move, as a railroad car, by prying the wheels
with a pinch. See <er>Pinch</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 4.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To seize by way of theft; to steal; to lift.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark> <rj><au>Robert Barr.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>to catch; to arrest (a criminal).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pinch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pinch
<hw>Pinch</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To act with pressing
force; to compress; to squeeze; <as>as, the shoe
<ex>pinches</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Hunt.)</fld> <def>To take hold; to grip, as a dog
does.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To spare; to be niggardly; to be covetous.</def>
<rj><au>Gower.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wretch whom avarice bids to <qex>pinch</qex> and spare.</q>
<rj><qau>Franklin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To pinch at</b></col>, <cd>to find fault with; to take
exception to.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au> </cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pinch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pinch
<hw>Pinch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A close compression, as
with the ends of the fingers, or with an instrument; a nip.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>As much as may be taken between the finger and
thumb; any very small quantity; <as>as, a <ex>pinch</ex> of
snuff</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Pian; pang.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Necessary's sharp
<xex>pinch</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A lever having a projection at one end, acting as a
fulcrum, -- used chiefly to roll heavy wheels, etc. Called also
<altname>pinch bar</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>At a pinch</b></col>, <col><b>On a
pinch</b></col></mcol>, <cd>in an emergency; <as>as, he could <ex>on a
pinch</ex> read a little Latin</as>.</cd><-- also in a pinch
--></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pinchbeck</ent>⟦br⟧
